  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV measures the small variations in timing between heartbeats while you sleep — a settled nervous system produces bigger swings, and load or stress compresses them. Your HRV of 46 ms this morning sits about 9 ms below your 30-day baseline of 55 ms, so it's a genuine dip, but a single-morning one. Your 7-day average HRV of 52 ms tells a calmer story — the week overall isn't sliding. Day-to-day HRV is noisy: a late meal, alcohol, or a hard evening workout often lines up with one low morning. I'd watch rather than worry — if the next two or three mornings stay down around this level, ease training and protect sleep. One low reading is a data point, not a verdict.",
